definition.value: Sediment that is part of a mangrove biome.
Mangroves are widely recognised as key ecosystems for climate change mitigation as they capture and store significant amounts of sediment organic carbon (SOC).
Sediment that is part of a salt marsh.
Solid material that has a waste role.
A dairy farm which is managed using practices certified to be organic by a competent authority.

value.value: A landfill that receives household waste.

label.value: biological nutrient removal during wastewater treatment

definition.value: A recycling process that uses microbes for the uptake of nitrogen and phosphorus during wastewater treatment.
A process in which includes the components of an environmental system as participants.
This is a convenience class for organisation and should not be used for annotation.

value.value: A type of land degradation in which terrestrial ecosystem becomes increasingly dry, typically losing its bodies of water as well as vegetation and wildlife.

A general and temporary condition of partial or complete inundation of normally dry land areas from the overflow of inland and/or tidal waters, and/or the unusual and rapid accumulation or runoff of surface waters from any source. A great flow along a watercourse or a flow causing inundation of lands not normally covered by water.

definition.value: A process which occurs within an atmosphere.
This class will be populated by inference and is primarily organisational.

value.value: A process by which thermal radiation from a planetary surface is absorbed by atmospheric greenhouse gases, and is re-radiated in all directions. Since part of this re-radiation is back towards the surface and the lower atmosphere, it results in an elevation of the average surface temperature above what it would be in the absence of the gases.
A process which diminishes the functioning of an ecosystem located on land.

definition.value: This could include, for example, reducing soil health, pollinator activity, or an ecosystem's ability  to sequester carbon.
A process which consists of all photosynthesis processes instantiated in an ecosystem.
A process which consists of all respiration processes instantiated in an ecosystem.
A biogeochemical process during which one or more chemical compounds are sequentially converted into a series of related compounds in a regularly repeating, periodic fashion.
A biogeochemical cycle which has carbon-bearing chemical entities as participants.

value.value: Establishment of a new forest by seeding or planting of nonforested land.

definition.value: Prior to afforestation, the land cover of a region must not include forests.

value.value: An ecosystem process during which the flora and fauna belonging to a forest are removed or destroyed.
The planting of trees in areas in where forests have previously been cleared.

definition.value: reforestation is reestablishment of forest where the forest recently existed[IPCC]
To be populated through inference. Do not use for annotation.

value.value: A process during which the populations in a community of algae in a marine or freshwater ecosystem undergo rapid growth, resulting in high concentrations of algal cells that occur only periodically and briefly in that ecosystem, relative to their concentrations through the majority of the planetary orbital period.
This class is under development. Note that cyanobacterial blooms are often confused with algal blooms. There is no globally recognised threshold beyond which community density enters a bloom state.
A process during which the rapid growth of algal populations that result in an algal bloom ceases, and cell densities begin to fall due to death, predation, and transport.

definition.value: A process during which the algal cells constituting an algal bloom produce biomass from abiotic components during photosynthesis.

definition.value: A process during which humans apply technology to alter the magnitude, duration, rate, or impact of an environmental process.
Relabel the obo foundry unique label to be generic process
An environmental process which is driven by the action of humans.

value.value: An action of exogenic processes (such as water flow or wind) which remove environmental material from one part of a planet's crust, transporting it to another location where it is deposited.

definition.value: An erosional process in which bedrock is converted from its solid form into a solute by the action of some solvent.

value.value: A process during which chemicals that are involved in natural ecosystem processes are transported or transformed, and which impact the activity of biological entities

definition.value: An environmental process which has water - in any of its states - as a participant.
This classes asserted subclasses will be moved away as it should be an inferred class.
A planned process during which human agents establish plant communities in ecosystems which have previously been, partially or wholly, stripped of existing plant communities.

value.value: Evapotranspiration is the sum of evaporation and plant transpiration from the Earth's land and ocean surface to the atmosphere.

Evaporation is a form of vaporisation which occurs when a portion of the surface layer of a liquid in contact with a gaseous material, which is not saturated with the evaporating substance, vaporises.

definition.value: Transpiration is the process of water movement through a plant and its evaporation from aerial parts of that plant, such as from leaves but also from stems and flowers.
Needs a process part "water transport" or similar and some link to plants to be complete.

value.value: An environmental system process that results in the introduction of contaminants into an environment.

definition.value: Pollutants may be material or immaterial (e.g. heat energy)
A pollution process during which particulates or other contaminants are released into a portion of air.

value.value: A pollution process during which contaminants are released into soil.

definition.value: A pollution process during which contaminants are released into water.

value.value: A pollution process during which plastic contaminants are released into an environmental material.

definition.value: An process in which environmental parameters and variables are continually assayed.
A planned process during which the amount of pollutants released into an environmental system is regulated.
A monitoring process that assays the level of environmental pollutants to determine the presence of effect of environmental pollution.
A pollution process that results in increased levels of pollutants in an urban environment.

value.value: Partially compacted granular snow, which has undergone several cycles of melting and refreezing while being compacted, usually found on the atmosphere-exposed surface of a glacier.

definition.value: Nv that survives a full season of ablation turns into firn.

value.value: Granular snow which contains a proportion of fused granules formed through melting and re-thawing while being compacted by the weight of overlying material and which contains interconnected gaseous pores.

definition.value: Firn derives from nv which has survived a full season of ablation and has undergone a metamorphic transition.

value.value: A material transformation process during which recently precipitated, powdery snow transitions into firn or nv through compaction and/or through cycles of freezing and thawing.

definition.value: Often, the weight of material deposited on top of powdery snow by, for example, mass wasting, can lead to nivation.

value.value: Any water ice that is part of a glacier.
